Most countries in Latin America have existing Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) laws that address impact mitigation and many also feature examples of voluntary compensation programs. A majority of the programs tend towards government compensation rather than a market-based system for offsetting impacts to biodiversity. EIA laws requiring mitigation/compensation measures (though not necessarily true offsets) are in place in Argentina, Belize, Uruguay, and Panama. Argentina and Costa Rica also maintain national-level compensation funds to channel compensation fees (Ecosystem Marketplace);

